"1377":"1377","from about 1250 to 1650":"from about 1250 to 1650","1463":"1463","1408":"1408","1407":"1407","1429":"1429","1417":"1416","1416":"1416","1427":"1427","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ashton Hall, Lancashire, England":"Ashton Hall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Heskethe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from Hesketh (Lancashire), Hesketh Grange in Felixkirk (North Yorkshire), or Hesket in the Forest (Cumberland). The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>hestr</i> ‘horse, stallion’ + <i>skeith</i> ‘course, track, race course’. The ancient Scandinavians were fond of horse-racing and horse-fighting, and introduced both pastimes to England."],"variants":[{"name":"Heskett","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Lancashire): variant of   Hesketh  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Thomas Heskethe was born in 1407, in Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Nicholas Hesketh, was 30 and his mother, Lady Margaret Ward of Minshull, was 30. He married Sybyl Lawrence in Ashton Hall, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1459, in Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1407–1459":"1407–1459","1408–1460":"1408–1460","1427–Male":"1427–Surnud","1429–Male":"1429–Surnud","–1463":"–1463","1377–1416":"1377–1416","2 October 1413":"2 oktoober 1413","um 1429":"umbes 1429","um 1427":"umbes 1427","1460":"1460","1459":"1459","12 November 1416":"12 november 1416","1389":"1389","1377":"1377","from about 1250 to 1650":"from about 1250 to 1650","1463":"1463","1408":"1408","1407":"1407","1429":"1429","1417":"1416","1416":"1416","1427":"1427","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rufford, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ashton Hall, Lancashire, England":"Ashton Hall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1407–1459":"1407–1459","1408–1460":"1408–1460","1427–Male":"1427–Kuollut","1429–Male":"1429–Kuollut","–1463":"–1463","1377–1416":"1377–1416","2 October 1413":"2. lokakuuta 1413","um 1429":"noin 1429","um 1427":"noin 1427","1460":"1460","1459":"1459","12 November 1416":"12. marraskuuta 1416","1389":"1389","1377":"1377","from about 1250 to 1650":"vuodesta noin 1250 vuoteen 1650","1463":"1463